        <type>variable</type>
        <definition>variable ASSERT_TS</definition>
        <argsstring>(variable var, string errorMsg)</argsstring>
        <name>ASSERT_TS</name>
        <param>
          <type>variable</type>
          <declname>var</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>string</type>
          <declname>errorMsg</declname>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Low overhead function to check assertions (threadsafe variant) </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>var</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>if zero an error message is printed into the history and procedure execution is aborted, nothing is done otherwise. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>errorMsg</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>error message to output in failure case</para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
Example usage: <programlisting><codeline><highlight class="normal">ASSERT_TS(DataFolderExistsDFR(dfr),<sp/>&quot;MyFunc:<sp/>dfr<sp/>does<sp/>not<sp/>exist&quot;)</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">do<sp/>something<sp/>with<sp/>dfr</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>Unlike <ref refid="_m_i_e_s___utilities_8ipf_1a34d370fb776d339d7f60e24c364eff69" kindref="member">ASSERT()</ref> this function does not print a stacktrace or jumps into the debugger. The reasons are Igor Pro limitations. Therefore it is advised to prefix <computeroutput>errorMsg</computeroutput> with the current function name. </para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
